{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 15:33:25.228491", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting diagnosis report\\nGoal: assess network health, detect anomalies, localize faulty devices, and identify root cause(s) based on the provided topology and the live data collected.\\n\\nSummary (high-level)\\n- Management plane (20.0.0.0/24) appears healthy: leaf and spine switches can reach the controller (20.0.0.100) and respond to pings on the management IPs.\\n- The tenant/data VLAN/subnet (10.0.0.0/24) is non-functional: hosts in 10.0.0.0/24 cannot ARP or ping each other and show 100% loss with \"Destination Host Unreachable\".\\n- Evidence indicates the Open vSwitch instances on the leaf/spine switches are in fail-mode \"secure\" and there are no OpenFlow dataplane flows installed — so data-plane forwarding for the tenant network is not happening.\\n- Likely root cause: OpenFlow controller is not installing the necessary forwarding rules (or the switches are not in a state where they accept/act on the controller\\'s flows). This results in switches dropping tenant traffic (fail-mode secure) and hosts being isolated at L2.\\n\\nWhat I ran / tests performed (representative)\\n- reachability summary (global): returned list of hosts and unknown ping statuses for many host-to-host pairs.\\n- Collected host network configs: get_host_net_config on hosts (host_1_1, host_1_2, host_2_1, host_2_2).\\n- Collected switch configs and OpenFlow state: ovs-vsctl show; ovs-ofctl show; dump-flows on leaf_1, leaf_2, spine_1.\\n- ICMP tests:\\n  - ping from host_1_1 -> host_2_1: 4/4 errors, 100% packet loss, From 10.0.0.1: \"Destination Host Unreachable\".\\n  - ping from host_1_1 -> host_1_2: same failure.\\n  - ping from leaf_1 -> controller 20.0.0.100: successful (0% loss).\\n- ARP table on host_1_1: multiple 10.0.0.x entries in ARP are incomplete (no HW address learned).\\n\\nKey observed outputs and their interpretation (evidence)\\n1) Host interface / ARP / ping behavior\\n- host_1_1:\\n  - inet 10.0.0.1/24 on eth0 (up)\\n  - pinging other hosts results: \"Destination Host Unreachable\" and 100% loss.\\n  - arp -n and /proc/net/arp show 10.0.0.x entries are incomplete (no MAC learned).\\n  Interpretation: Hosts are configured and their NICs are up, but they cannot get ARP responses / L2 reachability to peers.\\n\\n2) Open vSwitch (leaf_1 / leaf_2 / spine_1) state\\n- ovs-vsctl show lists Controller \"tcp:20.0.0.100:6633\" and fail_mode: secure on bridges.\\n  - Example: Bridge leaf_1 -> Controller \"tcp:20.0.0.100:6633\", fail_mode: secure\\n  Interpretation: OVS is configured to use the SDN controller and is in secure mode (packets without matching flow rules are dropped).\\n- ovs-ofctl show leaf_1 / leaf_2 / spine_1 show datapath/port features, ports are physically UP and show 10GB-FD, but the LOCAL interface of the bridges is reported as PORT_DOWN / LINK_DOWN:\\n  - LOCAL(leaf_1): ... PORT_DOWN / LINK_DOWN\\n  - LOCAL(leaf_2): ... PORT_DOWN / LINK_DOWN\\n  - LOCAL(spine_1): ... PORT_DOWN / LINK_DOWN\\n  Interpretation: internal bridge interface has no link state (no IP assigned); not necessarily the core issue but shows the bridge internal port is not in an L3 state.\\n- ovs-ofctl dump-flows <bridge> returned no flows (empty).\\n  Interpretation: No OpenFlow rules are present on the switches to forward/learn tenant traffic. With fail_mode=secure, this means dataplane packets will be dropped.\\n\\n3) Management connectivity\\n- ping from leaf_1 to controller (20.0.0.100) succeeded:\\n  - 3 packets transmitted, 3 received, rtt ~0.7–0.9 ms.\\n  Interpretation: Management-plane IP connectivity from the switches to controller is working. So the control network (IP connectivity) is up.\\n\\nSynthesis / anomaly detection\\n- Anomaly: Tenant subnet 10.0.0.0/24 traffic is not being forwarded between hosts. Hosts cannot learn ARP entries for each other; host-to-host pings fail with \"Destination Host Unreachable\".\\n- Anomaly: OVS bridges have no OpenFlow flows installed (ovs-ofctl dump-flows returned empty).\\n- Setup detail that explains the observed behavior: Bridges are set to fail_mode: secure. In secure mode, if no flow entry matches a packet, the packet is dropped (contrasts with \"standalone\" or \"secure with controller fallback\" behaviors). With no flows installed by the controller, the data-plane is effectively down even though physical ports are up.\\n\\nLocalization (where the failure manifests and is most likely caused)\\n- Manifestation: Isolation of 10.0.0.0/24 hosts on leaf switches (host ARP entries incomplete; host pings fail).\\n- Localized device(s)/layer:\\n  - OVS datapath on leaf switches (leaf_1 and leaf_2) and spine_1 — these devices have no forwarding rules and are dropping packets.\\n  - The SDN controller (20.0.0.100) or the OpenFlow session/logic that should program the switches — although management connectivity exists, controller is apparently not programming forwarding rules for the tenant network.\\n- Most likely point of failure: control-to-data-plane interaction (controller not installing L2/L3 flows for tenant/subnet), causing the switches to drop tenant traffic due to fail_mode=secure.\\n\\nProbable root cause(s)\\n- Primary hypothesis: Controller is not programming the switches with the required forwarding rules for the tenant 10.0.0.0/24 network (controller application not running, misconfigured, or controller-switch OpenFlow connection is not resulting in table programming).\\n  Evidence:\\n  - ovs-vsctl shows controller configured on each bridge, and switches can ping the controller (control-plane connectivity OK).\\n  - However, ovs-ofctl dump-flows on leaf and spine returned zero flows — no dataplane flows exist to forward ARP/ICMP between host-facing ports.\\n  - Hosts in same L2 subnet cannot ARP/learn each other — indicating L2 forwarding isn\\'t happening on the switches.\\n- Secondary possibilities (less likely but related):\\n  - Controller connected but misconfigured (controller may accept switches but not have logic to install learning L2 flows).\\n  - Controller uses a different OpenFlow port/version or expects different handshake parameters (but ovs-vsctl shows controller endpoint and switches are able to ping controller).\\n  - Switches\\' internal bridge/local ports are DOWN, which could be symptomatic of an OVS configuration/state that prevents bridging behavior — but the primary immediate cause remains the lack of flows + fail_mode=secure.\\n\\nImportant evidence excerpts (from collected outputs)\\n- fail_mode and controller:\\n  - \"Controller \"tcp:20.0.0.100:6633\"\" and \"fail_mode: secure\" (ovs-vsctl show for leaf/spine)\\n- No flows present:\\n  - ovs-ofctl dump-flows leaf_1 --names => (empty)\\n  - ovs-ofctl dump-flows spine_1 --names => (empty)\\n- Hosts cannot reach each other:\\n  - host_1_1 -> host_2_1 ping: 4 packets transmitted, 0 received, +4 errors, 100% packet loss; \"From 10.0.0.1 icmp_seq=X Destination Host Unreachable\".\\n- Incomplete ARP entries on hosts:\\n  - host_1_1 arp table shows entries for 10.0.0.2/3/5/16 incomplete / hardware address all zeros.\\n- Management reachability:\\n  - leaf_1 ping 20.0.0.100: 3/3 received, rtt ~0.644/0.783/0.883 ms.\\n\\nConclusions\\n- The tenant/data-plane for 10.0.0.0/24 is down: hosts are effectively isolated at L2.\\n- The network devices (leaf_1, leaf_2, spine_1) have IP connectivity to the controller (management network OK), but there are no OpenFlow dataplane rules on the switches to forward tenant traffic.\\n- The most plausible root cause: controller is not (or cannot) programming flows for tenant forwarding, and because switches are in fail_mode=secure they drop unmatched traffic. This results in L2 isolation even though underlying links and management connectivity are up.\\n\\nNotes / suggested next diagnostic checks (no remediation steps provided)\\n- Verify OpenFlow connection status and controller logs to confirm whether the switches have an active OF connection and whether the controller application is installing flows (for example: check controller logs, or check \\'ovs-vsctl get Controller <bridge> is_connected\\' or \\'ovs-appctl -t ovsdb/ovs-vswitchd\\' status).\\n- Inspect controller application state to confirm it is programmed to provide basic L2 learning or required flows for the tenant network.\\n- On the switches, examine any OpenFlow error counters or controller-related messages to see if flow install attempts are failing.\\n\\nIf you want, I can:\\n- Run targeted commands to confirm the OpenFlow \"is_connected\" state for each bridge and to attempt to list any controller messages.\\n- Check controller reachability from other switches or query any available controller logs (if accessible).\\n- Collect additional OVS statistics (ofproto/trace, port stats, or ovs-appctl outputs) to further narrow whether flows were attempted and rejected., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='8f2ec9a1-2249-41a8-a01b-cc4c9f92a7e2'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
